segments.text: Not anybody, really, of any great concern.
He's just somebody that the Republican Party put in, but that's just voice and opinion.
And I guess it says in itself that, yes, I do have a lot of resentment for people who legally evaded the draft or legally found themselves a way out.
And it took many years to really learn that the Selective Service was more concerned with its upper echelon young men
in keeping them out of the war and away from military service as it was.
It was really interesting for me to learn in South Vietnam, we had 19-year-olds at war long before they did.
And what is even more appalling is to know that most of the people that we fought were very young kids.
The VC, they weren't old people.
They were 30 years and younger.
And it's surprising how many 12 to 15-year-olds I bumped into.
So in respect, yeah, I have a lot of resentment.
But it's not something that's just one of those things that just no respect.
And Vice President Quayle just fits in that category.
Let that be on the record.
Okay, returning to the United States after your tour of duty, did you find it hard?
Like, here you were just in a jungle, and then you get back to here.
The transition period?
Yeah.
Let me tell you, when I got my orders, when I received my orders, you know, you're finally going back home, and
Things are relatively easy going in the processing, processing out.
But then I always go back and remember that second lieutenant.
And I began to look back in the servicing areas, back at Benoit, the hatred, the racial indifferences, the Yankee
Rebel hatred is still there.
I'm still seeing it today around the country.
The black movements and your Uncle Tom's and your Harlem and Watts and Southside Chicago Loop, which I grew up in, is still there.
When I was going through my process in the back, my mind was always there.
There's still another war going on, a war that
we're probably never going to find a solution to.
I don't know.
But it's just, it was there.
And that transition always kept me alert.
The moment that plane took off, it just felt like being drained.
All of the emotional ties of knowing that you're finally going home were there.
And I remember all the guys there just, everybody just screamed and hollered.
Wanted something to drink, but I don't think there was anything on the plane to drink.
Except whatever, somebody happened to sneak in on the plane.
And all of a sudden, you know, we were all happy guys.
For one, for less than an hour, we were all happy guys, you know.
And then somebody lit up a joint.
It started smoking, and immediately officers converged on him.
This guy was a criminal now, you know.
And it wasn't even funny anymore.
And we're going like, you're going to actually arrest and court-martial this guy now.
And less than 20 minutes ago, you're over there hugging and kissing the guy.
I mean, not kissing, but hugging him and shaking his hand and saying, job well done, soldier, and all this and that.
And then turn right around, and he makes just a slight mistake.
And now we're in a whole different world.
Transition was rather difficult, because even when I did get back,
Especially in California, it's so relaxed out there.
Right.
That's essentially the immediate transition.
When I came back home, it was like, oh, where you been, Claude?
I ain't seen you in two years, man.
I've been doing this.
I said, yeah, well, I've been gone.
Well, that's basically it.
When you left, yeah, when you first left, did you feel guilty that you were going to get to go home, or did you feel, well, I did my time?
Yeah, I always felt I did the best I could, but yeah, you do feel bad.
You leave friends, you leave people.
I never really got real close to anybody.
I tried not to.
It was important to me not to get too attached.
Mm-hmm.

It's just one of those psychological feelings that you don't want to deal with, having to see someone that you've been sitting there talking about his problems or your problems, and then feel a close attachment.
Now, some guys did, simply because they got a little more out of it, or closeness than I did, but there was nothing, you know, the only sad part about it was knowing that
I was no longer going to be there, and I really didn't want to be there.
The transition period was very brief for me.
I immediately came home to find a whole different world a year later, two years later, and then finding all the different movements that were going on here, the different fads.
It was essentially like another chapter in your life.
Turn the page.
Start a new day and a new writing, something new.
to do and so I went back to school.
Did it make you bitter that back here not a lot of people knew actually what was going on and like you said, they came up and asked you, you know, where have you been?

Yeah, well, yeah, they were more concerned about the girl that, you know, that was, they met at the dance the other night, you know, and I'm going, it's nice to talk, oh, she was good looking, you know, and I'm going, yeah, I guess so, yeah.
No.
There was no bitterness.
It's just that I knew what I had done.
I can't help it if they didn't know what they were doing, what they didn't know.
There are just so many people in this country that are so ignorant to reality.
And at that particular time, unless you were a student, then you became aware.
Take the number of students versus the population.
You have very little.
So everybody still dealt with only knowing what the media told them and what they read in the paper, which essentially was played down because of the Nixon administration.
So, you know, it's just one of those things.
The people are more concerned with their everyday life, you know, and it's good that you're back now, not you're back here, it's okay, you know.
I'm going, yeah, thanks a lot, you know.
This is what I lived for, right.
Is there anything...
Anything of importance that you think, essentially maybe that you learned about yourself from going to Vietnam or that you learned in general?
In general?
Basically we should get involved in an incident like that.
I think we have a very similar incident going on down in Nicaragua, down in Central America.
It's just one of those things that we're pumping too much money
pumping too many guns.
We're going to find ourselves either as taxpayers spending more money in that direction.
And it's essentially the same history that Vietnam went through.
If we did anything, we should be able to look back and see why Vietnam became such an important issue.
If I learned anything, I learned to read more.
And I learned to be able to search more for reasons and to really do something with and commit myself because I have a better understanding.
I was young.
Not a lot of us were young.
Look at the age group.
The age is the difference between World War II and the real goal we had then versus the goal we had in Vietnam.
So essentially if I've learned anything it's become cognizant.
What about anything that you might want to talk about that I haven't asked you?
We didn't really deal too much with drugs.
That seems to be the most important thing that went on for a long time.
You know, I'll give you an incident, and, you know, we'll just look at it from there.

But I remember one day, you know, it was kind of a rather long day for me because I helped out at a hospital, at one of the evac hospitals, and I came back to the dispensary, and the surgeon that worked with us, I had a few beers there, so I drank them.
I felt a little more at ease and then I happened to walk outside and two little Puerto Rican guys come over to me and they said, hey doc, you got any needles there?
I said, needles?
You know, I need some needles.
And that's when I began to really see more and more heroin.
I mean, it was probably there, I just didn't pay attention to it.
And I began to
to start seeing that, you know, these guys, you know, they're really down into it.
So I gave him a few needles and told him, you know, keep it cool, and he says, yeah, sure, you know, we'll be okay.
One of them OD'd that night.
But I went outside, and there by one of the sides of the bunks there, several of the guys were together.
And one of them had a pipe.
We used to do this on the fire base.
And the fire base is about the only time you ever did any smoking, if you did any smoking.
Because essentially, you have a secure perimeter.
You had a lot of guys that didn't smoke.
So somebody was always alert.
So you didn't really have to deal with getting, if you did get high, you were pretty well secured.
But this particular situation, this one guy had this pipe, and he had this Cambodian weed dipped in opium.
And they asked me, hey, you want a hit?
I went, sure, I'll take a hit.
I got nothing else to do, right?
I mean, what else could go wrong?
So I took a good whiff of that.
you know, held it long enough and released it and took another one, held it long enough and released it and then slowly, very slowly began to stand up and then things started getting blank, you know.
And for the next 36 hours it seemed like, that time period, I remember going over the showers and I remember standing under the shower and I stood there at least two hours
And this is late at night.
I don't remember what time I left the showers, but the Hoochie Maids came in the next morning and I was still in there.
But the showers were off.
And it was just like, what happened?
I mean, this stuff was good, but Jesus Christ, what happened?
And I remember going back and just laying in the bunk.
And like I said, 36 hours later, I woke, I really woke out of it.
And they told me what was in it, but they said, you were acting real strange, you know.
I said, thanks a lot.
From then on, I never touched the stuff.
I always asked what it, you know, it was just dipped in opium or not.
But as far as just smoking, I'd smoke.
But
So I learned very quickly, you know, what drugs were about, and I just said, hey, you know, it's just not something that I need to get into.
And it was surprising that I had so many friends, well, not friends, but fellow soldiers there that were into heroin, because it was so cheap.
And here again, you know, the problems of the field didn't seem so important anymore.
The problems of being
among each other seemed greater.
So there really was a big problem and it was really strange that you couldn't trust the people that you were immediately working with.
And that's just, you know, something that we even have today among ourselves, you know, just in everyday life.
So that was one important issue that always stood firm is just how bad the drug scene was.
And a lot of it had to do with just the fact that we had no purpose, you know.
And that we were, and those of us that had been out in the field, you know, had come to a realization that we may not come home the next day.
And so, you know, on the fire bases, you went out and had a great time.
You know, if you got drunk and ended up beating each other up, you know, it was the next morning you knew that, black eyes or not, you're getting on that helicopter and you're rolling out, you know.
Did it affect you in any way, like out in the field fighting, knowing that, did you start to be more careful at any point, or worry about what you were doing, or was it like that all the time?
Well, to begin with, I never went out in the field intoxicated by drugs or beer.
And you're so physically fit to begin with, and you sweat it all out that you don't carry that with you.
No, the only thing that bothered me was the racialness.
You know, he went back to the fire base, and the blacks would go one way, the Mexicans would go the other.
Puerto Ricans go in another direction.
The hillbillies from Arkansas would go in their direction.
The New York cats would go in their direction.
And then all of a sudden, you know, they'd be cussing and fighting, you know.
And then the next morning, we're sitting in a helicopter.
We all, those of them who got into each other, you know, are still mad at each other.
But now we're working with each other.
We're fully...
fully automated, you know?
And we've got all the automatic weapons and the scopes and the grenade launchers, the shotguns with us.
So we really carried that grunt.
I'm discussing
what it was like being in the field and how you felt being in the field.
Well, as I was saying, if we really carried that grudge, we had an opportunity to do something right then and there.
But it's surprising, just the whole theater in itself, that we were more concerned about our duties during the daytime and the time that we were out in the field

that we didn't care about our inner thoughts and yet as soon as we get back to a fire base or to a main secure zone where we can forget about the jungle then all of a sudden the 18 or 20 years prior to going to Vietnam all came back into play and you really began to see that the trust among each other all only depended upon how you really felt among each other
And that's the grudges of black hating white and rich against poor and more educated versus uneducated all stepped into play.
And that's something that your interactions among so many different people from all over the country and the hostilities that we have in our own country were with us there.
And it wasn't like you're a friend, you know, one day, and the next day you're willing to kill each other.
So different times you just, not everybody got along, but when it came down to the actual having to engage.
And one of the platoons adjacent with us one time, although there was a lot of grudge against this West Point second lieutenant, that in one particular incident,
which ended in his life, was the fact that he was so concerned about increasing his rank that one of the Claymore mines has tripped.
And for some reason, he wanted to be the first one out there to check it out.
He ended up tripping over another one, which ended his life.
There was no remorse for him.

you know that's a shame because you know you know you're only close because you're having to work with each other but at the same time the grudges from back home and the grudges that have always played in the back of your mind were there and uh it just you know to me there was a not caring attitude I think that was a low point in my life is the sense that that uh
I learned to just be the type of person that dehumanized.
There was no want, no caring at one particular point.
It was just something that stood out the most.
We were there.
You weren't going home right away regardless.
I guess that's it, unless there's anything... No, basically that's, you know, I know that in your class and, you know, you're young, you're having to look back and see.
You're hearing more about Vietnam and the people.
I even just read this morning that General Gieff is doing fine and well in his little fishing town in Dubuque or something like that.
It's right next to Houma, Louisiana.
And that was funny to listen.
I mean, just to look in the paper and catch that, because he was so much of a strong person and president, you know, prime minister, that is.
South Vietnam during 65 and 68.
But there's so much news coming out nowadays, especially with movies and stuff, with people trying to
bring back old feelings and bringing back the triumph.
But I don't think we should ever forget.
We should ever really think back and not feel that those were very tormented years.
And to those of us that took part in it, it's very, very close to the many of Americans that lost sons and daughters.
I include daughters because I guess they were females.
I didn't know of any, but still.
it's not something we should ever forget and we should ever really feel.

It's just that today in this country, you know, you see so much, so much hatred, you know, so much discontent, so much cheating, so much stealing, and I don't think, maybe it's not any different than it was back in the 50s, but it's just something that, you know, the direction in which this country goes is very important.
I guess that's why many of us, you know, we finally, we're getting together, we're finally beginning to look
and to ask the questions together.
How did the movies today about Vietnam, do they mean anything at all to you, or are they just movies?
Well, they're movies.
That's some points in time.
There are a few movies in certain instances that can bring you right directly to that confrontation period.
But I guess the greatest movie that I ever saw had anything to do with Vietnam was called Hearts.
I know, Hearts of Mind.
Yeah, Hearts of Mind.
Did you see that?
We saw it in class.
Yeah, because it was so direct, and it was something that I visioned, that I visually saw, part of.
And, you know, it's just, you know, it's not Hollywood.
Right.
That's really important, is that we do look at our country as a broad foreign policy,
with an open mind and an open thought of what we're really there and what is our purpose.
But that stands out.
The PBS's 13 series of the 10,000 Day War stands out because it is documented.
Very few people see them.
They're more concerned with coming home and the deer hunter.
And the only thing good about the deer hunter was the fact that it was
well acted.

De Niro played the part very well, but the sentimental value of knowing and the transition and all the things that you went through as a soldier there put a tear in your eye when you walked out of there.
I know it did me, and it wasn't so much because I related to any of the things that happened there.
Some of the things I saw, some of them I didn't.
But at the same time, the

I guess it's the speed at which life went at that particular time period and those months that I was there really stood forward and I guess I just felt it in the movie and in the very end when they sang the final song.
Movies like that generally don't really appeal to me.
Platoon was just another
another version of a John Wayne movie of years ago.
I mean, I understand Hollywood plays so much to capture your thoughts, but sometimes they go a little bit abroad.
You don't really see it and feel it.
And it's just a shame that the things that went on over there, the death, to see the women and children
simply because they were in an area they weren't supposed to be in, will always stay in the back of my mind.
And to remember that soldier crying out about, damn it, he didn't want to die here.
I want to go home, but I don't want to go home in a bag.
That always stands out.
And to come out of the field, that's serious, come out of the field of being among all that,
moisture, all those leeches, all those snakes, you know, which a couple of them crawled over my leg, you know.
I was so tired, I didn't want to move.
All I did was, one particular incident, one crawled over and he went toward a Harlem cat and was so tough, you know, he ran.
I told him there was a snake coming after him.
Just all those things, you know, just
that happen out in the field, and then you come back and get reassigned into a base very close to the major city of Saigon.
And then across the air base there at Benoit, they've got a theater that's just like the one back home.
You've got a long bin, and they've got tennis courts just like the ones back home.
And a lot of libraries and all kinds of goodies, you know.
And you're going, now these are for the officers.
And for the people of the higher echelon, we've got to go over there and sit with bunkers and pull guard duty.
It just really makes you think about life in general and what you feel is democratic and what isn't.
So then essentially you're asking the question, why was I there?
And I think in the very end, I'll always feel the same way.
I went there to honor myself as a member of the country, of this country.
And more important to me is to honor my family as well as honor my dad, because I always held him with a lot of pride and a lot of feeling.
He went through it.
My uncles went through it.
And between me and another cousin, that was it as far as the family was concerned.
And hopefully nobody else will ever have to go.
But here again, our present conditions don't warrant that.
And it's highly probable that we're going to find border confrontations real soon.
And I just hope that our foreign policy will always remember those trying years and use all of that history to reinvent
to not recreate what essentially was our problem in Vietnam.
I hope I've just been helpful.
Sure.
Everything will help.
Thank you very much.
Okay.
Good day.
